Date: 14 Feb 2013
Source: Times of India [edited]
http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/Elephant-death-sparks-anthrax-panic/articleshow/18492141.cms


Elephant death sparks anthrax panic
-----------------------------------
Anthrax fear grips state tiger reserves yet again. The sudden death of an adult makna (male without tusks) elephant in Jaldapara Wildlife Sanctuary has set the alarm bells ringing among forest department officials. Though attending vets ruled out poisoning as the cause of death, they were cautious not to specify any other reason.

The carcass of the elephant was found on Tuesday morning [12 Feb 2013] at the Siltorsa compartment in the west range of the forest. During examination, veterinary doctors found blood oozing out from the nose and mouth of the animal which has sparked panic among foresters.

While anthrax might be a remote possibility, nothing can be said for sure until the test reports for viscera samples are received, said sources. The samples have been sent to Regional Disease Diagnostic Laboratory in Kolkata.

The elephant carcass was buried hastily to prevent the virus from spreading.

The forest department has also started a thorough screening of the forests in North Bengal to find out whether any other elephant or animal has died in the past few days. Foresters said the last case of anthrax was reported from Jaldapara in the 90s when few elephants and rhinos had died due to this virus. [It is not a virus. It is a bacterium.]

"So far we have not spotted any other carcass in the forests. Had the disease spread, there would have been more deaths. We are taking every necessary step to arrest the disease from spreading. We have also asked the animal husbandry department to check whether any case of anthrax was reported among the cattle in forest villages," said BK Sood, conservator of forests, wildlife, Northern Circle.

The department is working in tandem with the veterinary department and has also planned to vaccinate cattle belonging to villagers and in fringe areas of the different forests in North Bengal. "We are keeping a close watch on the rhino population as well. Besides, we have stopped our captive elephants from grazing inside the forest, especially where the carcass of the elephant was found," Sood added.

The forest department has 80 kunki (trained) elephants in Jaldapara, Gorumara National Park, Buxa Tiger Reserve Forest and Mahananda wildlife sanctuary. It is now checking if all these elephants are properly vaccinated. If not, they will be vaccinated.

[Byline: Pinak Priya Bhattacharya]

