[Anthrax was suspected and samples were sent to Kalkata for analysis; nothing has been heard since. The elephant has been buried. Though he was bleeding from orifices, we do not suspect anthrax. Instead we suspect one of 3 novel herpesviruses -- EEHV1A, EEHV1B and EEHV2 -- all members of the Proboscivirus genus and are the only ones associated with acute haemorrhagic disease. This virus is quite common in Asian elephants.

A total of 3 novel herpesviruses EEHV1A, EEHV1B and EEHV2 were identified originally as the causes of fatal haemorrhagic disease in 1999. However since 2007 many more types have been detected with a total number of 12 species and 2 subspecies. The 8 known EEHV types are all members of the _Proboscivirus_ genus and are the only ones associated with acute haemorrhagic disease. (Garner et al., 2009; Latimer et al., 2010). EEHV causes fatal haemorrhagic disease, attacking endothelial cells (blood vessels, heart and similar organs) among Asian elephants and has become a very serious problem. This disease has a sudden acute onset and preferentially targets calves between the ages of one and 8 years (with more than half of those between one and 3 years of age). The 1st case was identified in 1995 at the Washington Zoo and reported in Science in 1999 (the earliest confirmed case is from 1983).

In the absence of the proven presence of _Bacillus anthracis_ in this elephant, we propose that a herpesvirus infection should be considered and investigated. One should remember that whatever the textbooks may say, blood extravsation in anthrax is more the exception than the rule; for example in the 1993 anthrax epidemic in the MacKenzie Bison Sanctuary in NWT Canada there were just a a couple of dead bison out of 175 with any haemorrhaging -- the rest were just dead. So realise that there may be other diseases to test for as well as anthrax when animals are bleeding from their orifices.

Mod.MHJ would like to acknowledge and thank Correspondent SB for her contributions to the above comment.

- Mod.MHJ

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1pSH.]
